snippet.textDisplay:
I would always open up the keyboard, remove the pcb and other electronic components, remove key caps, and place all of it in a tub with some warm soapy water and let it soak for 5 mins. Rinse, dry, reassemble. Since just the chassis, and none of the electronics were in contact with water, there's no long wait time, and the keyboard comes out completely clean.

That said I've also spilled 8oz glass of iced tea through the top of the case, all over my motherboard and graphics card while running a game, and it still ran for 3 more years until I sold it several years ago, so pc parts definitely aren't as delicate as people sometimes believe.

snippet.textDisplay:
Having had to clean and repair keyboards a few times, I don't see any way that will work, and even if it did, and it survived, water still inside will slowly corrode the contacts.
It would have been nice if they separated the case to verify that it was dry(I think I can guarantee it wasn't, unless they put them under a heat lamp or baked them at a really low temp) and clean.
For membrane keyboards, once the water gets between the layers, I don't see it coming out very easy at all without disassembly.
Also, I like to use deoxit on all contacts, which you cannot do without disassembly.
snippet.textOriginal:

snippet.textDisplay: The secret to wet washing any electronics is drying. I've worked in electro-mechanical disaster restoration for over 20 years and have stripped and washed literally thousands of PC's (as well as far more complex cabinets and research equipment) as long as the items are dried thoroughly then they'll generally be fine (using de-ionised water and rinsing properly helps as well). To dry them relatively quickly stick the parts in the oven for 12 hours @ 50C. Be warned though, don't go over 50C or you'll melt the plastic components.

snippet.textDisplay: You're supposed to take the keyboard apart before putting it in the dishwasher (i.e. separating the top and bottom half and the electronic board). You lose the warranty anyway. Lowest temperature, with soap. Everything is spotless clean. Drying took some hours, not days, because there is not closed space where water could get trapped.

snippet.textDisplay:
Before finishing the video the best way is clearly:
1. Remove all key caps
2. Wipe with a soft cloth (wet if preferred)
3. Blow out all switches with compressed air/shake keyboard (If wet method is used in step 2 use a dry cloth to clean all key caps)
4. Replace all key caps after 4-6 hours (if using non-water method time can be reduced to 2-4 hours)
5. Keyboard is as good as new, repeat as soon as desirable. For best results 6 months to 1 years per clean is recommended as well as using wet clean for key caps with extended drying time
